	(35,1,'2013-05-11 20:11:40','2013-05-12 00:11:40','<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Google Analytics, average visit duration is “the average time duration of a session”. Makes sense.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">So if my average visit duration is 2:46, does that mean most people spend 2:46 on my website? Probably not.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2 dir=\"ltr\">I’m about to show you something and it’s going to hurt</h2>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://porcelainduck.localhost/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/google-analytics-engagement1.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-37\" alt=\"google-analytics-engagement\" src=\"http://porcelainduck.localhost/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/google-analytics-engagement1.png\" width=\"924\" height=\"300\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A while ago Google added an “Engagement” section in Analytics (found under Audience &gt; Behavior). I bet if you check you’ll have a pretty big number of people that spend under 10 seconds on your site. The ratios seen above aren’t uncommon.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">And why does it matter how long people spend on your site, anyway? People tend to think longer is better, that means they’re “engaging” with your website. But what if that means the things they were looking for were hard to find? What really matters is whether they did what you wanted.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is easier for website that are selling something, because then nothing matters except sales. But even with a blog, sure, I want people to read my posts, and a really low visit duration would signify some sort of problem. But I also want people to share my posts, and follow me on Twitter. That’s a specific, measurable action and will tell me if I’m doing a good job - not how long someone spends on my website.</p>\r\n&nbsp;','What does average visit duration really tell you?','','publish','open','open','','what-does-average-visit-duration-really-tell-you','','','2013-05-11 20:51:36','2013-05-12 00:51:36','',0,'http://porcelainduck.localhost/?p=35',0,'post','',0),
	(36,1,'2013-05-11 20:10:26','2013-05-12 00:10:26','','google-analytics-engagement','','inherit','open','open','','google-analytics-engagement','','','2013-05-11 20:10:26','2013-05-12 00:10:26','',35,'http://porcelainduck.localhost/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/google-analytics-engagement.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),
	(37,1,'2013-05-11 20:10:54','2013-05-12 00:10:54','','google-analytics-engagement','','inherit','open','open','','google-analytics-engagement-2','','','2013-05-11 20:10:54','2013-05-12 00:10:54','',35,'http://porcelainduck.localhost/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/google-analytics-engagement1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),
	(38,1,'2013-05-11 20:11:34','2013-05-12 00:11:34','<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Google Analytics, average visit duration is “the average time duration of a session”. Makes sense.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">So if my average visit duration is 2:46, does that mean most people spend 2:46 on my website? Probably not.</p>\n\n<h2 dir=\"ltr\">I’m about to show you something and it’s going to hurt</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://porcelainduck.localhost/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/google-analytics-engagement1.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-37\" alt=\"google-analytics-engagement\" src=\"http://porcelainduck.localhost/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/google-analytics-engagement1.png\" width=\"924\" height=\"300\" /></a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A while ago Google added an “Engagement” section that’s found under Audience &gt; Behavior. I bet if you check you’ll have a pretty big number of people that spend under 10 seconds on your site. The ratios seen above aren’t uncommon.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">And why does it matter how long people spend on your site, anyway? People tend to think longer is better, that means they’re “engaging” with your website. But what if that means the things they were looking for were hard to find? What really matters is whether they did what you wanted.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is easier for website that are selling something, because then nothing matters except sales. But even with a blog, sure, I want people to read my posts, and a really low visit duration would signify some sort of problem. But I also want people to share my posts, and follow me on Twitter. That’s a specific, measurable action and will tell me if I’m doing a good job - not how long someone spends on my website.</p>\n&nbsp;','What does “average visit duration” really tell you?','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision','','','2013-05-11 20:11:34','2013-05-12 00:11:34','',35,'http://porcelainduck.localhost/2013/05/35-revision/',0,'revision','',0),
	(39,1,'2013-05-11 20:52:39','2013-05-12 00:52:39','<p dir=\"ltr\">According to Google Analytics, average visit duration is “the average time duration of a session”. Makes sense.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">So if my average visit duration is 2:46, does that mean most people spend 2:46 on my website? Probably not.</p>\n\n<h2 dir=\"ltr\">I’m about to show you something and it’s going to hurt</h2>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://porcelainduck.localhost/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/google-analytics-engagement1.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-37\" alt=\"google-analytics-engagement\" src=\"http://porcelainduck.localhost/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/google-analytics-engagement1.png\" width=\"924\" height=\"300\" /></a></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">A while ago Google added an “Engagement” section in Analytics (found under Audience &gt; Behavior). I bet if you check you’ll have a pretty big number of people that spend under 10 seconds on your site. The ratios seen above aren’t uncommon.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">And why does it matter how long people spend on your site, anyway? People tend to think longer is better, that means they’re “engaging” with your website. But what if that means the things they were looking for were hard to find? What really matters is whether they did what you wanted.</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This is easier for website that are selling something, because then nothing matters except sales. But even with a blog, sure, I want people to read my posts, and a really low visit duration would signify some sort of problem. But I also want people to share my posts, and follow me on Twitter. That’s a specific, measurable action and will tell me if I’m doing a good job - not how long someone spends on my website.</p>\n&nbsp;','What does average visit duration really tell you?','','inherit','open','open','','35-autosave','','','2013-05-11 20:52:39','2013-05-12 00:52:39','',35,'http://porcelainduck.localhost/2013/05/35-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),
	(40,1,'2013-05-11 19:46:54','2013-05-11 23:46:54','<p dir=\"ltr\">I made a new website last winter and I finally got off my ass (or on my ass?) and got it online. Formerly a Tumblr, and a photo site before that, this one\'s built from scratch with the hottest buzzwords including HTML5, CSS3, media queries, WordPress, and Instagram.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">You can even social media! And I hope you do.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2 dir=\"ltr\">Why the switch from Tumblr to WordPress?</h2>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">I\'ve spent a lot of time with WordPress and I like it well enough. I just wanted more control and a place to play around with some stuff. A lot of Tumblr blogs are used for curating content rather than just creating your own, and I feel that\'s how a lot of visitors think about them. I may keep a tumblog going for that reason - Tumblr <em>is</em> pretty cool. Plus I find editing Tumblr themes is a pain in the ass.</p>\r\n\r\n<div></div>','Website v3','','inherit','open','open','','1-revision-12','','','2013-05-11 19:46:54','2013-05-11 23:46:54','',1,'http://porcelainduck.localhost/2013/05/1-revision-12/',0,'revision','',0),
	(41,1,'2013-05-11 20:40:04','2013-05-12 00:40:04','<p dir=\"ltr\">Whenever I need quick look at keywords on a given topic I do a quick Google search. Without hitting <em>return</em>, I let autocomplete tell me what people might be searching for. As an example, what are popular searches and/or content about Halifax, Nova Scotia?</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://porcelainduck.localhost/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/google-autocomplete-seo-keyword-tool.png\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-42\" alt=\"google-autocomplete-seo-keyword-tool\" src=\"http://porcelainduck.localhost/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/google-autocomplete-seo-keyword-tool.png\" width=\"693\" height=\"140\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">I wouldn’t base my SEO strategy on this, but it’s a great for quick insights. Emphasis on quick.</p>','Google Autocomplete is a pretty good keyword tool','','publish','open','open','','google-autocomplete-is-a-pretty-good-keyword-tool','','','2013-05-11 20:44:59','2013-05-12 00:44:59','',0,'http://porcelainduck.localhost/?p=41',0,'post','',0),
